Winn King wrote:
&gt; For the static portlet it would be very useful if you could have
&gt; multiple ones on a site with different styling.
">

I thought so, but I'm not sure how to do it right.

One option is to have a &quot;borderless&quot; tickbox, which basically just
renders the text without any portlet styling around it. Then you can
just use the HTML in the portlet itself to do whatever styling you need.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; So a unique css style(s) would be auto-generated for each new static
&gt; portlet you added like the main sections now have auto-generated styles
&gt; (section-front-page, section-services, etc.)
">

The problem with an auto-generated CSS class is that it's hard to
predict. If I have five static text portlets, what do I call each of
them? How can the CSS author be sure that the generated classes won't
change if the site admin moves portlets around?

Perhaps there could be some kind of registry of outer CSS classes and a
drop-down box, but I'm not sure where such a registry would be
maintained. I don't want to create too much infrastructure just for this
one portlet.

Martin

