&lt;snip /&gt;

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;   1. A &quot;static text&quot; portlet. This has a title (required), a body text
&gt; field using the Kupu editor (required), a footer (optional) and a URL
&gt; (optional), which if set will turn the header and footer into links.
">

It's not too late to make changes, but here's what I've done for now:

- The static text portlet has an &quot;omit border&quot; tickbox. When checked,
*only* the text of the portlet is rendered (inside a div). The header,
footer, details URL and standard portlet border/formatting is not included.

- Whether &quot;omit border&quot; is selected or not, a CSS class is generated
from the header text (which is still mandatory).

For example, if a static text portlet has the header &quot;Welcome message&quot;,
with &quot;omit border&quot; turned on and the text &quot;Hello /world/&quot; (entered with
Kupu, the last word in italics), the output would be:

&lt;div class=&quot;portletStaticText portlet-static-welcome-message&quot;&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Hello &lt;em&gt;world&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

If omit-border were false (the default), it would include the standard
portlet &lt;dl&gt; structure:

&lt;dl class=&quot;portlet portletStaticText portlet-static-welcome-message&quot;&gt;
&lt;dt class=&quot;portletHeader&quot;&gt;
&lt;span class=&quot;portletTopLeft&quot;/&gt;
&lt;span&gt; Welcome message &lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class=&quot;portletTopRight&quot;/&gt;
&lt;/dt&gt;
&lt;dd class=&quot;portletItem odd&quot;&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Hello &lt;em&gt;world&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;span class=&quot;portletBottomLeft&quot;/&gt;
&lt;span class=&quot;portletBottomRight&quot;/&gt;
&lt;/dd&gt;
&lt;/dl&gt;

There's also the option to provide a portlet footer and an optional
&quot;details&quot; link in the case with omit border is off.

This feels minimally clunky and should cover a range of use cases.
Opinions welcome!

Martin

