Hi Martin,

We've been brainstorming around the office about possible portlets. Here are
their comments, albeit a bit muddled:

I would propose:
- hide/show Collection's Description (default: show)
- hide/show Collection's rich Body (default: hide)
- hide/show listings' Descriptions (default: hide)

The use cases for the first two are the following:
- limit to 1 (maybe 2) items in the listing; include a verbose description
(ie show description; hide rich body)
- limit to 1 (maybe 2) items in the listing; include a verbose *rich*
description (ie hide description; show rich body)
- show a bunch of items in the listing; hide both description and body

Random content portlet: I was thinking the portlet would have a dropdown to
select a particular
content type.  Perhaps also a setting for how many to show.

Random image portlet, a subset of the random content portlet.

Recent comments portlet: So that you can easily what content on the site has
recently generated
discussion.  Jon Stahl has mentioned this one, so may have a clearer use
case in mind.

Media Portlet – This ideas are probably best combined but here are two
subideas of this.
o       Slideshow Portlet - Grabs slide show by flickr or other online photo
gallery id and/or tags and/or sets and allows you to configure things like
(how many slides, show titles (y/n))
o       Video Portlet – Same Idea
o       Podcast Portlet – Same Idea

Editable Portlet – Connects to a page that you edit.

News Clipping portlet – you can connect the portlet to one or many RSS
feeds.  When you are logged in it allows you to see news items from the
feed. You can click items that you like and add comments and decide if you
want to write your own into to the content or leave it as is.

Google Analytics Portlet – This portlet connects with Google Analytics and
shows you page relevant results.  What is the rank of the page you are on.
How many visitors has it has.  What is the top link on the page. Bounce
rate, top keyword.

Cheers,

- Veda

